'''Luis Ricardo Mejía Cajar''' (born 16 March 1991) is a Panamanian professional footballer who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Uruguayan Primera División]] club [[Club Nacional de Football|Nacional]] and the [[Panama national football team|Panama national team]].

==Club career==
Nicknamed ''Manotas'', Mejia made his professional debut playing with [[Tauro F.C.|Tauro]] in 2007.
 
In 2008, he was transferred to Uruguayan side [[Centro Atlético Fénix]], but finally made his team debut on 21 August 2010 on a match against [[Tacuarembó F.C.|Tacuarembó]], being rewarded as the man of the match.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.diariopro.net/en-el-extranjero/item/536-brillante-actuaci%C3%B3n-de-luis-mej%C3%ADa-en-su-debut |publisher=Diariopro |title=Brillante actuación de Luis Mejía en su debut |accessdate=25 August 2010 |date=23 August 2010|language=Spanish}}</ref> His outstanding performances called the interest of various team of Europe.

In January 2011, he was loaned for 6 months to [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]] but was never able to win a place in the first team, so he had to cope with playing in the reserve team.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://diariopro.net/en-el-extranjero/item/1068-luis-%E2%80%9Cmanotas%E2%80%9D-mej%C3%ADa-presentado-como-jugador-del-toulouse |publisher=Diariopro |title=Luis "Manotas" Mejía presentado como jugador del Toulouse  |accessdate=8 January 2011|date=5 January 2011|language=Spanish}}</ref>

Upon his return to [[Centro Atlético Fénix|Fénix]] in June 2011, he cemented his position in the starting lineup of the team. In the [[2012–13 Uruguayan Primera División season]], he played 27 games where they conceded 37 goals in the annual table and finished in seventh position, one spot away from qualifying for the Copa Sudamericana.<ref>{{cite web|date=14 May 2013 |publisher=[[Tenfield]] |title=Fénix: vienen para observar a Luis Mejía y Hernán Novick |url=https://www.tenfield.com.uy/fenix-vienen-para-observar-a-luis-mejia-y-hernan-novick/}}<!-- auto-translated from Spanish by Module:CS1 translator --></ref> In the [[2013–14 Uruguayan Primera División season|2013–14 championship]] he played 18 games where Fénix conceded 22 goals, again resulting in a seventh-place position.<ref>{{cite web|date=4 February 2014 |publisher=Pordeciralgo |title=“Soy casi un uruguayo más” |url=https://www.pordeciralgo.com.uy/blog/2014/02/soy-casi-un-uruguayo-mas}}<!-- auto-translated from Spanish by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>

After several impressive seasons as a top-performing goalkeeper in the Uruguayan top flight, Mejía signed for [[Club Nacional de Football|Club Nacional]] in 2015. For his first three seasons at the club, he was back-up goalkeeper to [[Esteban Conde]], but obtained the starting position in the team for the [[2018 Uruguayan Primera División season|2018 season]]. In [[2019 Uruguayan Primera División season|2019]], he made 24 league appearance as Nacional won their forty-seventh domestic title.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.babagol.net/blog/2019/12/13/nacional-penarol
 |publisher=babagol|title=Nacional or Peñarol? The Never-Ending Uruguayan Championship Saga  |accessdate=7 July 2025|language=english}}</ref> After losing the starting role in the team to the [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguayan international]] goalkeeper [[Sergio Rochet]] for the starting role in 2020, Mejía returned to Fénix for one season, and then left Uruguay for the first time since 2011 to join [[Unión Española]] for the [[2022 Chilean Primera División]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/articles/sergio-rochet-interview-goalkeeper-uruguay-celeste-fifa-world-cup-qatar-2022
 |publisher=FIFA|title=Rochet: Uruguay have a great side who are hungry  |accessdate=7 July 2025|language=english}}</ref>

He returned to Nacional in [[2024 Uruguayan Primera División season|2024]], retaking the position as the primary goalkeeper in the team following Rochet's transfer to [[SC Internacional|Internacional]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/uruguay/nota/_/id/13406268/sergio-rochet-su-sentimiento-vigente-por-nacional-y-las-cualidades-de-luis-mejia |publisher=espn deportes|title=Sergio Rochet: su sentimiento vigente por Nacional y las cualidades de Luis Mejía  |accessdate=7 July 2025|language=spanish}}</ref>

==International career==
Mejía was part of the [[Panama national football team|Panama U-20]] squad that participated in the [[2007 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] in Canada. He was the youngest goalkeeper in the world cup and the revelation. He was also part of the [[Panama national under-20 football team|Panama U-20]] squad that participated in the [[2011 CONCACAF U-20 Championship]] where his outstanding performances led them to qualify to the [[2011 FIFA U-20 World Cup|Youth World Cup]] in Colombia.<ref>{{FIFA player|267702}}</ref>

His senior international debut for [[Panama national football team|Panama]] came on 8 June 2009 against [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]], in a [[Friendly match]].<ref name="NFT">{{NFT player|id=31823}}</ref>

He was part of the [[Panama national football team|Panama U-23]] squad that participated in the [[2012 CONCACAF Men's Olympic Qualifying Tournament]] which they could not qualify to the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2012 Summer Olympics]].

In 2011, he was called up by [[Julio Dely Valdés]] to play the [[2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].

In the [[2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], he played 2 matches and conceded 6 goals as Panama were eliminated in the group stage. Mejía was also called up for the [[2023 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2023]] version of the tournament, where his side finished as runners-up as they lost the final 1-0 against [[Mexican national football team|Mexico]] at [[SoFi Stadium]], in which he was the back-up goalkeeper to first-choice [[Orlando Mosquera]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/678990/panama-mexico
 |publisher=ESPN|title=Mexico 1-0 Panama: Gold Cup final  |accessdate=7 July 2025|language=english}}</ref>

He was similarly a substitute goalkeeper for the [[2024 Copa América]], where Panama were eliminated in the quarterfinals, eventually losing to [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/703948/panama-colombia
 |publisher=ESPN|title=Colombia 5-0 Panama: 2024 Copa quarter final  |accessdate=7 July 2025|language=english}}</ref>

